HEADWORD: Ophicleide
<hw>Oph"i*cleide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ophicl⟦eacute⟧ide</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>'o`fis</grk> a serpent + <?/,
gen. <?/, a key. So named because it was in effect the serpent, an old
musical instrument, with keys added.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A
large brass wind instrument, formerly used in the orchestra and in
military bands, having a loud tone, deep pitch, and a compass of three
octaves; -- now generally supplanted by bass and contrabass tubas. It
developed from the older wooden instrument called the
<contr>serpent</contr>.</def> <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of
Music).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

